Here's the full migration. The code has three `Thread.Abort`-dependent patterns that must change:

## Pattern Inventory

| Original Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Internally called `Thread.Abort` — throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Return an `IActionResult`; no explicit end needed |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse: true` called `Thread.Abort` | Return `Redirect(url)` from the action |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in modern .NET; dead code | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core / .NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Web Forms event handler → MVC action returning IActionResult
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Response.Clear / AddHeader / Write / End → single FileContentResult
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Response.Redirect("/login", true) → return Redirect()
            // No Thread.Abort, no ThreadAbortException
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // catch (ThreadAbortException) — REMOVED: never thrown in .NET 8
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

1. **`Response.End()` is gone** — In ASP.NET Core, returning an `IActionResult` ends the response. There is no `Response.End()`. Calling it was always a `Thread.Abort` in disguise.

2. **`Response.Redirect(url, true)` — the `true` is the trap** — The `endResponse: true` parameter triggered `Thread.Abort` to prevent code after the redirect from executing. In ASP.NET Core, `return Redirect(url)` exits the action method naturally via control flow — no abort needed.

3. **Remove `catch (ThreadAbortException)` entirely** — In .NET Framework, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw `ThreadAbortException` as a side effect, so developers swallowed it. In .NET 8 `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`, so this catch is dead code. More importantly, swallowing it masked real bugs — the new pattern makes control flow explicit.

4. **`User.Identity` can be `null`** — ASP.NET Core doesn't guarantee a non-null `Identity`. Use null-conditional access (`User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`).

5. **No more code-behind event model** — Web Forms `btnExport_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)` handlers don't exist. Each action is an `[HttpPost]` endpoint returning `IActionResult`. Wire up your forms/AJAX to POST to `/Report/Export`.

6. **For long-running requests, use `HttpContext.RequestAborted`** — If `GenerateReport()` is expensive, pass the cancellation token:
   ```csharp
   var data = await GenerateReportAsync(HttpContext.RequestAborted);
   ```
   This is the cooperative cancellation equivalent of the old abort model.
